me></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF035055%2F1"><gtr:id>EF7FA031-5B3B-4078-9A9B-7488E1904BEB</gtr:id><gtr:title>Planning and Managing under Uncertainty: A Flexibility Perspective</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F035055/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Managers often have to make decisions before they are confident about their choices. The more dynamic the market environment; the longer the project period; the more stakeholders involved; and the less experience available, the greater the decision-makers' information inadequacy. However, the resulting risk of wrong decisions can be mitigated by staying flexible. For example, pursuing contracts with two partners instead of one reduces failure risk. Unfortunately, it also has the effect of reducing purchasing economies of scale. If managers are unable to handle flexibility and gauge its value, they are likely to create less flexibility than needed, useless types of flexibility, or too much flexibility.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Exploring this challenge, the award research conceptualises factors that drive the costs and benefits of strategic flexibility, including processes and structures inherent to organisations. The programme of work encompasses empirical analysis of the influence of organisational capabilities to manage flexibility over time, execute options, and govern the decision-making process. It is shown that these capabilities contribute more to performance than the ability to gauge flexibility value (an implicit assumption of real options works). &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>83031</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>0B2A38D4-1179-453D-86BA-F47BC154868B</gtr:id><gtr:title>Becoming Aware of the Unknown: Decision Making During the Implementation of a Strategic Initiative</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Organization Science</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/db0cf30373324884cbb1d8b67a9a9227"><gtr:id>db0cf30373324884cbb1d8b67a9a9227</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Klingebiel R</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2013-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfacfac381bb10</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><g